<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="284" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,625]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,473,290,313]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">Diagnosis of the female.</emphasis>
Female can be recognized from all remaining females of the species of the genus by the elongate copulatory ducts (
<figureCitation box="[439,563,325,348]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1501,1523]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,668,1480]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,668,1481]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Scopocira crotalica Costa &amp; Ruiz, 2014. 9 female, dorsal view; 10 epigyne, ventral view; 11 same, cleared, dorsal view; 12 same, cleared, dorsal view. Scale bar = 1.00 mm (9); 0.15 mm (10 – 12)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/239701/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
Figs 
<number box="[493,563,325,348]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="284" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,625]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,609,360,383]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
Description. Female (ICN-Ar 
<number box="[540,596,360,383]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="6754.0">6754</number>
).
</emphasis>
Total length 
<number box="[751,801,360,383]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="3.33">3.33</number>
. Carapace orange, 
<number box="[1005,1051,360,383]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="1.47">1.47</number>
long, 
<number box="[1120,1167,360,383]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="0.96">0.96</number>
wide, 
<number box="[1240,1287,360,383]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="0.67">0.67</number>
high (
<figureCitation box="[1356,1423,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1501,1523]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,668,1480]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,668,1481]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Scopocira crotalica Costa &amp; Ruiz, 2014. 9 female, dorsal view; 10 epigyne, ventral view; 11 same, cleared, dorsal view; 12 same, cleared, dorsal view. Scale bar = 1.00 mm (9); 0.15 mm (10 – 12)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/239701/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
Fig. 
<number box="[1407,1423,360,383]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). OC 
<number box="[196,242,394,417]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="0.64">0.64</number>
long. Anterior eye row 
<number box="[508,555,394,417]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="1.04">1.04</number>
wide and posterior 
<number box="[774,821,394,417]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="0.95">0.95</number>
wide. Sternum 
<number box="[995,1042,394,417]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="0.58">0.58</number>
long, 
<number box="[1113,1160,394,417]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="0.42">0.42</number>
wide. Labium 
<number box="[1326,1372,394,417]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="0.14">0.14</number>
long, 
<number box="[151,198,429,452]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="0.2">0.20</number>
wide. Chelicerae with four large retromarginal teeth, and five small promarginal teeth. Legs 
<number box="[1249,1305,429,452]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="4132.0">4132</number>
, yellow, all laterally with dark longitudinal stripes. Spination: femur I–IV d 
<number box="[870,883,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="1.0">1</number>
di, reduced in size; tibia I 
<date box="[1196,1258,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
v 
<number box="[1220,1235,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="2.0">2</number>
- 
<number box="[1243,1258,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="2.0">2</number>
</date>
- 
<number box="[1265,1280,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="2.0">2</number>
- 
<number box="[1288,1303,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="2.0">2</number>
; II 
<date box="[1346,1405,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
v 
<number box="[1370,1386,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="2.0">2</number>
- 
<number box="[1395,1405,464,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1</number>
</date>
-2; metatarsus I–II 
<date box="[319,382,498,521]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
v 
<number box="[339,354,498,521]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="2.0">2</number>
- 
<number box="[363,378,498,521]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="2.0">2</number>
.
</date>
Abdomen cream-colored, rounded, with a dark longitudinal stripe, crossed by two transverse dark stripes (
<figureCitation box="[237,306,533,556]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1501,1523]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,668,1480]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,668,1481]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Scopocira crotalica Costa &amp; Ruiz, 2014. 9 female, dorsal view; 10 epigyne, ventral view; 11 same, cleared, dorsal view; 12 same, cleared, dorsal view. Scale bar = 1.00 mm (9); 0.15 mm (10 – 12)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/239701/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
Fig. 
<number box="[290,306,533,556]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). Epygine with large spermathecae, with elongate and externally placed copulatory ducts (
<figureCitation box="[1297,1423,533,556]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,258,1501,1523]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,668,1480]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,668,1481]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Scopocira crotalica Costa &amp; Ruiz, 2014. 9 female, dorsal view; 10 epigyne, ventral view; 11 same, cleared, dorsal view; 12 same, cleared, dorsal view. Scale bar = 1.00 mm (9); 0.15 mm (10 – 12)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/239701/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="284">
Figs 
<number box="[1353,1423,533,556]" pageId="3" pageNumber="284" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12</number>
</figureCitation>
), which correspond with the embolus length of the male of the species.
</paragraph>
